The goal of DOTS the RPG is to bring about collaboration to create/translate braille rule books and associated gaming aids for the Visually Impaired in order to empower the Visually Impaired to run, play, and experience the magic of tabletop role-playing with complete independence. There are a few tactile dice on the market, but there are no rule books, adventures, or character sheets produced in braille...DOTS is hoping to be the Stylus & Slate RPG Project that blows the doors wide open for this overlooked demographic. Join us and participate on our journey to open the world of tabletop gaming up for the Visually Impaired!

We want any and all game designers, those who work with the visually impaired, and any gamers who are willing to work towards this goal to jump in and collaborate. We also are hoping to draw visually impaired gamers to the group who are willing to provide honest and meaningful insight and feedback regarding the efforts being put forth.

Let's all work together to make the world of RPGs accessible to the visually impaired!

Stan Maddox is located in Columbus, Indiana, in the United States of America. He is a 14-year Veteran of the U.S. Army and Army Reserve. He served as an M60A1 Armor Crewman, Tank Commander, Tank Commander Instructor, and Drill Sergeant.

Stan earned his General class amateur radio (ham) license in August 2017. His call sign is KD9JFD. He has a particular interest in man-portable mobile rigs, which dovetails nicely with his interest in map reading and land navigation, a subject he enjoyed teaching while he was in the military.

Stan is a member of the American Radio Relay League (ARRL), the Bartholomew County Amateur Radio Emergency Service® (ARES), the South Central Indiana Communications Support Group (SCICSG), the Columbus Amateur Radio Club, the National Rifle Association (NRA), the National Model Railroad Association (NMRA), and the U.S. Army Brotherhood of Tankers (USABOT).

Stan is an active musician who has been playing drums since 4th grade. Currently, he plays Tenor drums in the Geneseo Knights Drum & Bugle Corps Alumni Drumline, and plays drum set in the Praise Band at Asbury United Methodist Church in Columbus, Indiana. He is married, and has two children.

Stan is also interested in railroads and model railroading. He has logged more hours riding behind steam locomotives, than he has spent flying in modern aircraft.

Hi everyone
I started making in 2016 after my father brought me my first printer, a CTC makerbot clone that really didn't work very well! After lots of mods I finally got it going and started printing things from Thingiverse but I really wanted to design my own things. I found some free 3d modelling software (A123D Design) online and off I went! I now have four printers of various types.
All the designs you see here were done in the last two years and are only a small sample of what I've made so far.
All my thingiverse items are fully 3D printable but I have other designs that are multi media, ie they use wood or foam or other materials mixed with 3d components.
I have just started a Facebook page named Bigbangcollectables with the aim of opening a shop in the future. Check it out and like and share if you can.
More models are available on my Etsy shop which I will be expanding over the coming months. Check it out.
https://www.etsy.com/shop/BigBangCollectables
Have fun always! Colin.
